We're running a standalone Razor view engine for e-mail templating. Sometimes, when disposing the corresponding service container, we run into ArgumentNullExceptions/IndexOutOfRangeExceptions inside ASP.NET Core within the `System.Buffers.DefaultArrayPool` class. From the outside it looks like `MemoryPoolViewBufferScope` is somehow used in a non-thread-safe manner during disposal, but we're far away from being sure.

Maybe we're doing something wrong when registering the components at the service collection:

    services.AddSingleton(_hostingEnvironment);
    services.AddLogging();
    services.AddSingleton<DiagnosticSource>(new DiagnosticListener("RazorHtmlRenderer"));
    services.AddSingleton<ObjectPoolProvider, DefaultObjectPoolProvider>();

    var mvcCoreBuilder = services.AddMvcCore();

    var fileProvider = new PhysicalFileProvider(_templatesDirectory);
    services.AddSingleton(fileProvider);

    mvcCoreBuilder.AddRazorViewEngine(o => o.FileProviders.Add(fileProvider));
    
    return services.BuildServiceProvider();

Are we registering something as singleton which should not be a singleton? The problem occurs in one out of 10 to 20 disposals. We checked that our Dispose is not called multiple times, so the problem resides somewhere during the Razor view engine disposal...

...any ideas on what we might doing wrong?

